 \section{Conclusion}
-\label{sec:conclusion}
 %% ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 
-This paper has been rewritten around the native-first requirement that RA proceed from finite combinatorial structure directly to Nature-facing macroscopic observables. In that form, its strongest claims are not continuum field-equation claims. They are claims about severance, boundary counting, sparse-regime topology change, and the possibility that observed lensing and expansion structure track realized causal history rather than a new hidden particulate sector.
-
-Within that programme, the severance formalism and the severed-link entropy observable remain the paper's strongest achievements. They are finite, graph-theoretic, and directly interpretable. The discrete boundary law and the interface regularity analysis together show how macroscopic boundary quantities can be discussed without elevating continuum area formulae to the status of primitive facts.
+Paper~III argues that RA's macroscopic value lies not in pretending GR and $\Lambda$CDM never existed, but in confronting the same observable domain through a different finite mathematical engine. In that engine, the deepest novelty is causal severance: a graph partition event with no close analogue in standard frameworks. Black-hole entropy then becomes the count of blocked irreducible causal channels, not the unexplained thermodynamic shadow of a continuum geometry. Sparse-regime response becomes a question about graph topology and inherited source history, not automatically about a new hidden particle sector. Late-time expansion becomes a question about fitting a finite inhomogeneous realized universe, not automatically about vacuum energy.
 
-The sparse-regime and cosmological sections are intentionally more modest. They now present a structural research programme rather than a closed derivation of galactic response, cluster lensing, or late-time expansion. The observational targets are still sharp: direct-detection null structure, large-radius orbital response, lensing offsets from present gas distribution, environment-sensitive BAO and supernova signals, and low-$\ell$ anomaly persistence. What is no longer claimed is that the full coefficient-level cartography of those phenomena has already been derived in native terms.
+None of this means the programme is complete. On the contrary, the paper is strongest exactly where it is most explicit about its limits. RA does not yet have the coefficient-level source law needed to claim every classical gravitational benchmark. It does not yet have a first-principles late-time expansion derivation. It does not yet have a theorem-level nucleation and low-$\ell$ closure. But it does have something distinctive and scientifically valuable already: a coherent finite account of partition, horizon entropy, and a concrete route by which the rest of the macroscopic domain can be attacked without importing the continuum ontology as primitive.
 
-This is an improvement in discipline, not a retreat. The paper is now clearer about what has actually been secured, what is being treated as phenomenological fit-kernel work, and what remains open. That makes the surviving claims stronger. The macroscopic RA programme is no longer presented as a proof that GR, $\Lambda$CDM, or Kerr geometry have been reproduced. It is presented as a finite graph-based attempt to predict the measured regularities of gravitating systems on RA's own terms.
-
-The next substantive tests are therefore straightforward: close the coefficient-level sparse-regime source law, decide whether historical source depth really controls cluster lensing, derive the environmental expansion signal from native structure rather than fit kernels, and sharpen the nucleation-to-low-$\ell$ chain. If those steps close natively, Paper~III will move from a disciplined macroscopic programme to a genuinely predictive one.
+If RA succeeds in the macroscopic sector, it will be because it continues to do what has made the programme productive so far: follow the discrete causal question all the way to the observable domain, compare honestly with the incumbent theories, and say plainly when the native closure is not yet there.
 
